                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Mittal son takes guard
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT AMP; PTI                                            
	New Delhi, Sept. 2: Telecom tycoon Sunil Mittal has appointed son Shravin as a manager in Bharti Airtel International (Netherlands), in another instance of youngsters following in the footsteps of their illustrious businessmen fathers.         
	Bharti Airtel shareholders yesterday approved Shravin Mittals appointment with an annual salary of up to 250,000 euros (nearly Rs 1.50 crore). Shravin is a graduate in accounting and finance from the University of Bath in the UK and has worked for more than three years in equity research and portfolio management with JPMorgan Chase, Ernst amp; Young, Merrill Lynch amp; Company, Deutsche Bank AG and IMG.        
	His remuneration will not exceed 250,000 euros per annum, or equivalent amount in any other currency. This will include salary, allowances, perquisites, bonus, incentives, retirement benefits and other facilities.        
	Mittal juniors current brief is to assist in the integration of Zain Africa with Bharti, the company said. He might be elevated to the board or equivalent position either in Bharti Airtel International Netherlands (BAIN) or any of the firms in which he is an employee.         
	The shareholder okay for Mittals appointment came on the day Bangalore-based Wipro decided to elevate chairman Azim Premjis elder son Rishad as the chief strategy officer of its information technology business. Both Shravin and Rishad are being groomed for a more prominent role in the family-promoted businesses, experts said.        
	Other top firms of India, including the Tata group, software maker Infosys Technologies and engineering group Larsen amp; Toubro (L amp;T), are on the lookout for their next leader.        
	Many prominent business families are busy in succession planning to avoid disputes such as the one that followed the death of Reliance founder Dhirubhai Ambani.         
	Godrej Group and the Munjals of Hero Group have drawn up succession plans. The Tata group and Infosys have set up panels to search for a successor to their respective chairmen, while L amp;T chief A.M. Naik has said his successor would be named by March 2012.         
	Among those who have brought on board next generation leaders from the promoter families are Shiv Nadar-led HCL Group and Kishore Biyani-promoted Future Group.        
	Roshni Nadar, daughter of HCL Technologies founder Shiv Nadar, and Ashni Biyani, Kishore Biyanis daughter, have joined their family firms.        
	Rama Prasad Goenka, the patriarch of Calcutta-based RPG Enterprises, is segregating the ownership of various group firms between his two sons Harsh and Sanjiv  to smoothen the transfer of control in one of Indias oldest business families. Sources said Harshs son, the 29-year-old Anant, a Wharton graduate who had worked with firms such as Accenture and Hindustan Unilever, was already a part of Ceat, an RPG group firm. Sanjivs son Shashwat, 21, is expected to join the family business in another two years.                                                                                                                                       
